Speaking to New Frame, one of the workers, Savy Mafindo, 52, from Zimbabwe, who marched from Church Square to the Union Buildings carrying an ironing board, said she wants the government to recognise them as workers and force employers to treat domestic workers with dignity. “Just having a cup of tea for 10, or even less than 10 minutes, you make it cooler, not hot, because you can’t take long drinking that tea. When you are having lunch, you find that your boss will call you again: ‘Come to work.’”
She said workers from other countries are even worse off because they “are so stranded”. “You want something to put on the table, so you will go for that money. But it’s not that you like that money.” Mafindo is not registered for the unemployment insurance fund (UIF) because she feels that insisting that her employer register her would jeopardise her position. 
<img data-attachment-id="6643" data-permalink="https://www.newframe.com/domestic-workers-overworked-underpaid-and-unprotected/28jun_domesticprotest_ih-3/" data-orig-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-3.jpg" data-orig-size="3600,2400" data-comments-opened="0" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;4&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;NIKON D850&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;17 June 2019: Domestic workers gathered at Church Square in Pretoria as they prepared for the start of their protest march. Domestic workers marched to the Union Buildings in Pretoria to demonstrate against unfair labour practices and low pay. Picture: Ihsaan Haffejee&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1560765015&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;\u00a9 New Frame&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;28&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;40&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.008&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-3" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-3-300x200.jpg" data-large-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-3-1024x683.jpg" src="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-3.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-6643" srcset="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-3.jpg 3600w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-3-300x200.jpg 300w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-3-768x512.jpg 768w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-3-1024x683.jpg 1024w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-3-960x640.jpg 960w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-3-480x320.jpg 480w" sizes="(max-width: 3600px) 100vw, 3600px" />17 June 2019: Domestic workers want the minimum wage raised from R15 an hour and more humane working conditions in general.
No protection 
Rose Kabani, 60, has been working as a domestic worker for 37 years. She said her employer has stopped paying her UIF. She sang along as the women marched: “Siya sebenza ekitchen kanzima – sisebenzela imali encane. (We are working in the kitchen – we are working for very little money.)”
Kabani supports her entire family because her husband and two children are unemployed. Her daughter wants to train to become a security guard, but Kabani can’t afford to give her money. “I have to buy food,” she said.   
“I am part of the march because I am underpaid,” said Lettie Skhosana, 44. “We are expected to work on holidays and weekends, but we are not paid.” Skhosana has worked as a live-in helper for 19 years. She sees her child only at the end of each month. She said R15 [an hour] is not enough but that “R20 or R30 could be a consideration”.  
<img data-attachment-id="6646" data-permalink="https://www.newframe.com/domestic-workers-overworked-underpaid-and-unprotected/28jun_domesticprotest_ih-4/" data-orig-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-4.jpg" data-orig-size="3600,2400" data-comments-opened="0" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;3.2&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;NIKON D850&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;17 June 2019: Lettie Skhosana, 44, hold up a sign in reference to President Cyril Ramaphosa\u2019s love for expensive buffalo\u2019s during a protest by domestic workers against unfair labour practices and low pay in Pretoria. Picture: Ihsaan Haffejee&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1560766365&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;\u00a9 New Frame&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;36&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;50&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.001&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-4" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-4-300x200.jpg" data-large-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-4-1024x683.jpg" src="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-4.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-6646" srcset="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-4.jpg 3600w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-4-300x200.jpg 300w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-4-768x512.jpg 768w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-4-1024x683.jpg 1024w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-4-960x640.jpg 960w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-4-480x320.jpg 480w" sizes="(max-width: 3600px) 100vw, 3600px" />17 June 2019: Lettie Skhosana’s sign refers to President Cyril Ramaphosa’s love of expensive buffalo.
Joana Matuibela, 52, disagrees with Skhosana. She wants workers to earn at least R45 an hour. “My child thinks I am choosing my work over him. At times, he thinks I do not care about him. But it’s not like that. I am oppressed at work.” She works on Saturdays and Sundays, and said her employer will neither change her working hours nor increase her salary. Instead, she was told: “Thousands of people are looking for jobs. You can leave my house.”  
Her employer has denied her the right to attend union meetings. “She told me, I must not rush cleaning her house. Because her dogs get frightened. I must work slowly to prevent frightening her dogs.” Skhosana described her working conditions as “emotionally draining”.  
As a single parent and a mother of two, Sonto Mahlangu, 42, doesn’t earn enough. She rents in Mamelodi, and spends R32 on a round trip to work. “What must change is the R15 [minimum wage]. We want to be paid decently. And count us in for medical aid. Don’t just give us Panado when we are sick,” she said.
<img data-attachment-id="6647" data-permalink="https://www.newframe.com/domestic-workers-overworked-underpaid-and-unprotected/28jun_domesticprotest_ih-5/" data-orig-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-5.jpg" data-orig-size="3600,2400" data-comments-opened="0" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;4&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;NIKON D850&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;17 June 2019: A member of the South African Police Service closes a gate at the Union Buildings preventing protesting domestic workers from entering. Domestic workers marched to the Union Buildings in Pretoria to demonstrate against unfair labour practices and low pay. Picture: Ihsaan Haffejee&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1560771701&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;\u00a9 New Frame&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;24&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;100&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.008&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-5" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-5-300x200.jpg" data-large-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-5-1024x683.jpg" src="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-5.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-6647" srcset="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-5.jpg 3600w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-5-300x200.jpg 300w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-5-768x512.jpg 768w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-5-1024x683.jpg 1024w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/28Jun_DomesticProtest_IH-5-960x640.jpg 960w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/0